[{"type":"{{","value":[["pagebanner"],["Pagebanner default.jpg"]]},"\n",{"type":"[[","value":[["File:Piotrkow Trybunalski Street On Old Town.JPG"],["thumb"],["Old Town"]]},"\n",{"type":"[","value":["http:\/\/www.piotrkow.pl\/ ",{"type":"'''","value":["Piotrków Trybunalski"]}]}," is second biggest city in the ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Łódź Voivodeship"]]}," of ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Poland"]]}," with around 80,000 inhabitants. It is the capital of Piotrków County and it's almost 800 years old. The city itself was portrayed in the movie ",{"type":"''","value":["Jacob the Liar"]}," starring Robin Williams.\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Understand"]},"\nAccording to tradition – not confirmed by historical sources – Piotrków was founded by Piotr Wlostowic, a powerful 12th century magnate from Silesia. The name of the city comes from the name ",{"type":"''","value":["Peter"]}," translated into Polish (",{"type":"''","value":["Piotr"]},"), in a diminutive form (",{"type":"''","value":["Piotrek"]},"). The town has been known in Yiddish as פּעטריקעװ or ",{"type":"''","value":["Petrikev"]},", in German as ",{"type":"''","value":["Petrikau"]},", and in Russian as Петроков or ",{"type":"''","value":["Petrokov"]},".\n\nAt first a market town and a place of the princes' tribunals (in the 13th and 15th centuries), Piotrków became an administrative centre (the capital of the district since 1418), and in the later centuries it also became an important political centre in Poland. While the importance of Piotrków in the political life of the country had contributed to its development in the 16th century, the city declined in the 17th and 18th centuries, due to fires, epidemics, wars against Sweden, and finally the Partitions of Poland.\n\nPiotrków had the first ghetto for Jews in occupied Poland, built as early as October 1939. Approximately 25,000 people from Piotrków and the nearby towns and villages were imprisoned there. 22,000 were sent to the ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Treblinka"]]}," extermination camp, while 3,000 were imprisoned in Nazi concentration camps.\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Get in"]},"\n\n",{"type":"===","value":["By plane"]},"\n",{"type":"'''","value":[{"type":"[","value":["http:\/\/www.airport.lodz.pl\/ Łódź Władysław Reymont Airport"]}]}," (",{"type":"{{","value":[["IATA"],["LCJ"]]},") is nearest international airport (about 50 km), but better choice is largest Polish ",{"type":"'''","value":[{"type":"[","value":["http:\/\/www.lotnisko-chopina.pl\/?lang=en Warsaw Frédéric Chopin Airport"]}]}," (",{"type":"{{","value":[["IATA"],["WAW"]]},") (about 160 km).\n\n",{"type":"===","value":["By train"]},"\n",{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"'''","value":["Piotrków Trybunalski"]}," terminal station for domestic trains. There are great (but slow) train links from all major Polish cities."]},"\nThe schedule of trains in ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Poland"]]}," ",{"type":"[","value":["http:\/\/rozklad.pkp.pl\/bin\/query.exe\/en?"]},"\n\n",{"type":"===","value":["By car"]},"\nPiotrków is located in junction of roads:\n\n",{"type":"*","value":[" road ",{"type":"'''","value":["A1"]},"; ",{"type":"'''","value":["E75"]}," ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Gdańsk"]]}," - ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Łódź"]]}," - ",{"type":"'''","value":["Piotrków Trybunalski"]}," - ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Częstochowa"]]}," - ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Katowice"]]}," "]},"\n",{"type":"*","value":[" road ",{"type":"'''","value":["8"]},"; ",{"type":"'''","value":["E67"]}," from state border with ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Lithuania"]]}," in ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Budzisko"]]}," trought ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Warsaw"]]}," - ",{"type":"'''","value":["Piotrków"]}," - ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Wrocław"]]}," and finally to state border with ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Czech Republic"]]}," in ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Kudowa-Zdrój"]]},"."]},"\n",{"type":"*","value":[" road  ",{"type":"'''","value":["12"]}," from state border with ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Germany"]]}," in ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Łęknica"]]}," trought ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Leszno"]]}," - ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Kalisz"]]}," - ",{"type":"'''","value":["Piotrków"]}," - ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Radom"]]}," - ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Lublin"]]}," and state border with ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Ukraine"]]}," in ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Beredyszcze"]]}]},"\n",{"type":"===","value":["By bus"]},"\nBecause of its location at a junction of major roads Piotrków Trybunalski is well connected to almost all major cities in ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Poland"]]}," by the PKS lines. From ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Warsaw"]]}," or ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Katowice"]]}," you can get to Piotrków Trybunalski by the Polski Express. There are some international lines like ",{"type":"[","value":["http:\/\/www.eurolines.com\/ Eurolines"]}," too.\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Get around"]},"\n",{"type":"'''","value":["Public transport"]}," is operated by ",{"type":"'''","value":[{"type":"[","value":["http:\/\/mzk.piotrkow.pl\/ MZK Piotrków Trybunalski"]}]},". The descriptions on bus stops are in Polish only. See the ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Polish phrasebook"]]}," if you feel uncomfortable. ",{"type":"[","value":["http:\/\/mzk.piotrkow.pl\/rozklad\/main.htm The schedules are here"]},"\n\n",{"type":"'''","value":["Taxis"]}," are another option, and they are quite cheap for a Westerner. However, you should make sure that there is a taxi sign atop the cab and that the driver has a permit. Best way is to use one of Taxi companies (",{"type":"''","value":["phone numbers"]},"):\n",{"type":"*","value":[" Radio Taxi Pilica - ",{"type":"''","value":["9625"]}]},{"type":"*","value":[" Radio Taxi Plus - ",{"type":"''","value":["9623"]}]},"\n",{"type":"==","value":["See"]},"\n\n",{"type":"*","value":[" Trybunalski Square, located about 1 km east from the train station. Is the old market square, with antique tenement houses"]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"{{","value":[["see"],["name=Royal Castl